destabilized during Shakespeare’s period—its place in the brain; its legitimacy as a form of knowledge; its pathologies; its relation to matter, light, and nature—reading these in concert with canonical works such as King Lear, Macbeth, and The Tempest. Shakespeare, Roychoudhury shows, was influenced by paradigmatic epistemic shifts of his time, and he in turn demonstrated how the mysteries of cognition could be the subject of powerful art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCognition in literature. 0aImagination in literature. 0aImaginationxHistoryy16th century. 0aImaginationxHistoryy17th century. 0aLiterature and sciencezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aLiterature and sciencezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPsychology in literature. 0aScience in literature. 4aHistory Of Science. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies.  aShakespeare, Renaissance theories of psychology, emerging fields of early modern science, imagination as a cognitive, exploits epistemological ferment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501726569?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501726569423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501726569/original  a978-3-11-060418-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Eng